ames © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Alexander Swinburne was born about 1260, in Capheaton, Northumberland, England, his father, William De Swinburne, was 26 and his mother, Mrs. Margaret De Swinburne, was 22. He married Agnes Thornhill about 1284, in Northumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. He died on 26 May 1309, in Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1260–26 May 1309":"umbes 1260–26. mai 1309","1260–1309":"1260–1309","1273–1326":"1273–1326","1279–Male":"1279–Surnud","1264–1332":"1264–1332","1285–1354":"1285–1354","1287–1349":"1287–1349","1289–Female":"1289–Surnud","1291–Female":"1291–Surnud","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","1235–1284":"1235–1284","1239–1282":"1239–1282","about 1260":"umbes 1260","26 May 1309":"26. mai 1309","1264":"1264","1285":"1285","1284":"1284","1273":"1273","1282":"1282","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","1349":"1349","1326":"1326","1235":"1235","1279":"1279","1289":"1289","about 1259":"umbes 1259","1354":"1354","1332":"1332","1287":"1287","1